Seadrill Ltd.: A Speculative Buy - Seadrill Limited (NYSE:SDRL) | Seeking AlphaSign in / Join NowGO»Seadrill Ltd.: A Speculative BuyFeb.20.17 | About: Seadrill Limited (SDRL) Achilles Research Long/short equity, special situationsSummarySeadrill is standing with its back to the wall; the company needs to restructure its balance sheet, and it needs to do so fast.The company has said recently that negotiations with lenders have not yet been successful, but that may change moving forward.Almost all negative outcomes are now priced into the stock, lending a lot of upside to Seadrill in case a restructuring agreement is reached.SDRL remains a speculative buy.Negative investor sentiment with respect to offshore drilling contractor Seadrill Ltd. (NYSE:SDRL) is off the charts. After the company gave an ill-received restructuring update at the end of January, investors dumped the stock, and kicked it into the bargain bin. I think that bad news are now sufficiently priced into Seadrill's shares, and that the offshore drilling company will be able to secure lender concessions and a financing package. Therefore, Seadrill's shares are a speculative buy. When it comes to selecting investments with compelling reward-to-risk combinations, one wouldn't necessarily come up with offshore drilling companies. The sector has been plagued by oversupply issues, lower contracting rates, and a cutback in investment spending on the part of big oil and gas companies that has thrown the offshore drilling sector into chaos. Seadrill has pushed back against those market forces by suspending its dividend, slashing operating costs for rigs, and deferring capital expenditures. Nonetheless, Seadrill - still - has a significant amount of debt sitting on its balance sheet, and that needs to be serviced. The company reported ~$8.9 billion in net interest bearing debt at the end of the September quarter, which is all that investors see these days. But Seadrill should not be counted out just yet. 


 Source: StockCharts.com Seadrill Should Be Able To Secure Lender Concessions And A Financing Package In a nutshell, Seadrill's capital structure is unsustainable, and needs to change, and it needs to change fast. In an effort to put the company on more stable financial footing, it has entered into negotiations with lenders to transition to a new capital structure, which would include the extension of bank maturities, the amendment of financial covenants, and raising new capital of at least $1.0 billion. Seadrill also wants to extend the maturity of unsecured claims. In the restructuring update the offshore drilling company provided in January, Seadrill said that negotiations with creditors were ongoing and difficult, but that they have not yielded positive results yet. What ticked investors off was the notion that Seadrill was "actively preparing various contingency plans" in case negotiations would go nowhere, and creditors would not want to play a role in SDRL's ongoing restructuring. After the announcement of the restructuring update, the shares slumped ~30 percent, reflecting concerns that Seadrill may slide into bankruptcy. That said, though, a lot of energy companies have been supported by their lenders during the energy market downturn, tilting the odds in favor of a restructuring solution for Seadrill also. As far as I am concerned, chances are that Seadrill will be able to hammer out an agreement with its lenders shortly, and be able to raise new capital before the West Eminence credit facility matures in April. Your Takeaway Seadrill will report fourth-quarter earnings on Thursday, and the company will likely give investors an update about its restructuring, and the progress it has made in terms of securing concessions from lenders. While there are certainly some bumps ahead in the road for Seadrill, I think the company will ultimately be able to come to an agreement with its creditors, and transition its capital structure to one that is more sustainable over the long haul. Almost the entire set of negative restructuring outcomes are now priced into Seadrill's shares, leaving a lot of headroom for a fast and hard recovery if the company reports a mutually beneficial restructuring agreement. Speculative Buy.
 If you like to read more of my articles, and like to be kept up to date with the companies I cover, I kindly ask you that you scroll to the top of this page and click "follow". I am largely investing in dividend paying stocks, but also venture out occasionally and cover special situations that offer appealing reward-to-risk ratios and have potential for significant capital appreciation. Above all, my immediate investment goal is to achieve financial independence.
Disclosure: I am/we are long SDRL. 
I wrote this article myself, and it expresses my own opinions. I am not receiving compensation for it (other than from Seeking Alpha). I have no business relationship with any company whose stock is mentioned in this article.About this article:ExpandAuthor payment: $35 + $0.01/page view. Authors of PRO articles receive a minimum guaranteed payment of $150-500.Tagged: Investing Ideas, Quick Picks & Lists, Basic Materials, Oil & Gas Drilling & ExplorationWant to share your opinion on this article? Add a comment.Disagree with this article? Submit your own.To report a factual error in this article, click hereFollow Achilles Research and get email alerts














